# BPS In-Place Migration Rules - Extracted from GitHub Analysis

**Source:** GitHub README `migration/cof/README.md` - In-Place Migration Approach with Automatic Updates

**Context:** Rules extracted from analysis of the BPS-based in-place migration strategy for CoF → RoA migration.

## Migration Strategy Rules

### MIG-BPS-001: In-Place Migration Approach
**Rule:** The migration SHALL be implemented in the CoF application using minor version upgrades (5.x.x), ensuring:
- All data structures remain compatible
- All changes are backward compatible (minor version requirement)
- Existing customers automatically receive updates without manual intervention
- When customers upgrade to RoA (6.0.0), data is immediately available
- No separate data migration process required
- No breaking changes allowed (semantic versioning constraint)

### MIG-BPS-002: Zero Data Migration Requirement
**Rule:** When customers upgrade from CoF (5.x.x) to RoA (6.0.0), SHALL require zero data migration because:
- Data is migrated to Forge Storage while customers are still on CoF
- Data structures are already compatible when upgrade occurs
- All data is immediately available in RoA after upgrade
- No additional migration steps required from customer

### MIG-BPS-003: Versioning Strategy
**Rule:** The versioning strategy SHALL follow:
- **CoF Application:** Current version 5.x.x (e.g., 5.1.0, 5.2.0)
  - Receives minor version bumps (e.g., 5.2.0 → 5.3.0)
  - Minor versions are automatically applied to customer installations
  - All changes must maintain backward compatibility
  - RoA-compliant changes gradually introduced in minor versions
- **RoA Application:** Released as major version (e.g., 6.0.0)
  - Major version requires manual customer upgrade
  - Gives customers time to prepare for transition
  - All data from CoF is compatible and immediately available
  - Customers can upgrade at their own pace

### MIG-BPS-004: Parallel Support Period
**Rule:** Both CoF and RoA applications SHALL be maintained simultaneously during transition period:
- Some customers remain on CoF while others upgrade to RoA
- Both versions must be supported, maintained, and receive updates
- Data compatibility ensures customers can upgrade at any time
- Requires careful coordination of updates and bug fixes for both versions

### MIG-BPS-005: New Installations Policy
**Rule:** Once RoA is released, new installations SHALL:
- Automatically use RoA version
- CoF version no longer available for new installations
- Existing CoF customers continue on CoF until they manually upgrade
- New customers automatically start on RoA from day one

## Idempotency Rules

### MIG-BPS-006: Idempotency Requirement (CRITICAL)
**Rule:** All migration steps SHALL be idempotent - they can be run multiple times without duplicating data.

**Rationale:**
- Critical for RoA application when customers upgrade - migrations may run multiple times
- Prevents data corruption and ensures reliable migration execution
- Follows existing pattern: SQL migrations use IF EXISTS/IF NOT EXISTS clauses

**Implementation Requirements:**
- SQL Migrations: Use IF EXISTS/IF NOT EXISTS clauses
- Data Transformations: Check for existing state before applying changes
- Data Migrations: Verify data doesn't already exist before inserting/updating
- Schema Changes: Use conditional DDL statements that are safe to run multiple times
- Validation: Test that running migrations multiple times produces the same result

## Batch Migration Rules

### MIG-BPS-007: Batch Migration Prerequisites
**Rule:** Batch migration SHALL require:
- Spaces and contents must be migrated to Fireflow first
- Ensures that all existing content is migrated
- Must iterate through every space of the instance
- Must iterate through every content item in each space

### MIG-BPS-008: Batch Migration Iteration Strategy
**Rule:** Batch migration SHALL iterate exhaustively:
- **No reliable pre-filtering:** Cannot determine if content has migration data without querying each one individually
- **Space-by-Space Processing:** System processes spaces sequentially, one at a time
- **Content-by-Content Processing:** For each space, iterate through all content items
- **Prerequisite Check:** Ensure content is already in Fireflow (if required)
- **Conditional Migration:** Migrate content-related data only if present
- **Query each content item individually** to check for migration data

**Performance Characteristics:**
- Lengthy process due to exhaustive checking
- Most spaces/contents don't have CDM-related data (in most instances)
- Iteration overhead is high, but migration data volume is relatively low
- Long processing time due to exhaustive checking, but manageable data volume

### MIG-BPS-009: BPS for Batch Migration
**Rule:** Batch migration SHALL use BPS (Batch Processing System):
- BPS supports long-running collectors - can run for hours to collect pages in big instances
- BPS handles the lengthy collection process required for batch migration
- Provides infrastructure needed to iterate through all spaces and content items
- BPS Backoffice provides interface with detailed information about migration
- Migration progress, status, and details visible through BPS backoffice

### MIG-BPS-010: Manual Control and Retry
**Rule:** Batch migration SHALL support:
- BPS Backoffice provides interface to trigger and monitor batch migration
- Can be triggered manually for selected instances through BPS backoffice
- Allows reattempting batch migration on specific instances
- Useful for retrying failed migrations or running migration on-demand
- Provides operational control over migration process
- Migration details, progress, and status available in BPS backoffice

## On-Change Migration Rules

### MIG-BPS-011: On-Change Migration Strategy
**Rule:** On-change migration SHALL ensure:
- Data modified after initial migration is also migrated
- Captures changes made during and after batch migration period
- Prevents data loss for changes made after batch migration

### MIG-BPS-012: Change Capture Process
**Rule:** When data is changed in CoF application:
- Change is applied to data storage (normal operation)
- Additionally, changed entity is added to AWS Queue for migration
- Dual-write approach ensures both immediate data persistence and migration queuing
- No performance impact - queue addition is asynchronous and non-blocking
- Handles updates, inserts, and modifications
- Changes are queued automatically without affecting CoF application performance

### MIG-BPS-013: Migration Queue Architecture
**Rule:** AWS Queue SHALL be used to queue entities to be migrated:
- Migration does not need to happen in real-time
- Queue-based approach provides:
  - Avoids overwhelming SQL database - controlled rate of migration operations
  - Easier log reading - better visibility and debugging of migration process
  - Better error handling - failed migrations can be retried from the queue
  - Scalability - can handle large volumes of entities without database overload
- Entities are queued and processed asynchronously
- Queue provides natural throttling and backpressure mechanisms

## Web Trigger Rules

### MIG-BPS-014: Hourly Scheduled Trigger (URL Registration)
**Rule:** Hourly scheduled trigger SHALL:
- Run on an hourly schedule
- Generate webtrigger URLs for each instance
- **Application Detection:** Must detect which application is running (CDM, CDC, or CDA)
- **Webhook Selection:** Use the appropriate webhook based on detected application
- Call the selected webhook in the CoF backend to register the URLs
- **URL Persistence:** CoF backend must persist these URLs
  - Options: Redis or user properties of the addon user
- Used to maintain a registry of webtrigger URLs per instance
- Ensures URLs are available for migration processes

### MIG-BPS-015: Static Webtrigger (No Data Egress)
**Rule:** Static Webtrigger SHALL:
- Receive migration items from external systems
- Accept migration entities in batches - designed to process multiple entities per request
- Insert or update data in the database
- **No data egress** - compliant with RoA requirements
- Available in both CoF and RoA applications
- Used for both batch migration and on-change migration
- URLs are registered via the hourly scheduled trigger
- Must handle both batch and incremental updates
- Batch processing improves efficiency and reduces overhead

**Status Response Limitations:**
- Can return a status from a predefined list
- Can indicate if entities have been correctly upserted
- Can indicate if there is some problem in some of them
- **Cannot identify which specific problem occurred**
- **Cannot identify which specific entity has the problem**
- Limited error reporting due to static webtrigger constraints

### MIG-BPS-016: Dynamic Webtrigger (With Data Egress)
**Rule:** Dynamic Webtrigger SHALL:
- Accept any SQL query for execution
- Used to validate migrated data
- **Has data egress** - allows querying and viewing data
- **Only available in CoF** - will NOT be available in RoA
- Critical for validation during migration period
- Provides the only way to view/query data in Forge during migration
- URLs are registered via the hourly scheduled trigger

### MIG-BPS-017: URL Registration Flow
**Rule:** URL registration SHALL follow:
1. Hourly scheduled trigger runs and generates webtrigger URLs for each instance
2. Scheduled trigger calls CoF backend webhook to register URLs
3. CoF backend persists URLs (Redis or user properties)
4. Registered URLs are used by external systems for migration

## Migration Architecture Rules

### MIG-BPS-018: CoF Application Database Writes
**Rule:** CoF application SHALL NOT write directly to the database:
- All database writes go through the Static Webtrigger
- Static Webtrigger processes items from the AWS Queue
- Ensures controlled and validated data insertion/updates

### MIG-BPS-019: Batch Migration Flow
**Rule:** Batch migration flow SHALL be:
1. Batch Migration Process iterates through every space and every content item
2. For each content:
   - Queries Fireflow (workflows, parameters, metadata, links)
   - Queries Versions Custom Content (document activities)
   - Retrieves OTP Tokens from Redis
3. Data is transformed (Fireflow → RoA format) and queued to AWS Queue
4. AWS Queue processes migration items and sends them to Static Webtrigger
5. Static Webtrigger inserts/updates data in Forge SQL Database

### MIG-BPS-020: On-Change Migration Flow
**Rule:** On-change migration flow SHALL be:
1. CoF Application generates events when data changes
2. Changed entities are queued to AWS Queue
3. AWS Queue processes migration items and sends them to Static Webtrigger
4. Static Webtrigger inserts/updates data in Forge SQL Database

### MIG-BPS-021: Validation Flow
**Rule:** Validation SHALL use:
- Dynamic Webtrigger (CoF only) allows validation queries against the database
- Provides the only way to view/query data in Forge during migration period
- Critical for validating migration success

## Entity Migration Rules

### MIG-BPS-022: Entities to be Migrated
**Rule:** The following entities SHALL be migrated from source system to CoF/RoA:
- Global Workflows - Workflow definitions at the global level
- Global Workflow Versions - Version history of global workflows
- Space Workflows - Workflow definitions at the space level
- Space Workflow Versions - Version history of space workflows
- Workflows Enabled or Linked for Space - Space-level workflow associations
- Space Workflow Parameters - Parameters configured for space workflows
- Content Current State - Current workflow state for each content item
- Content Document Activities - Activity history for content items
- Content Linked Workflow - Workflow associations for content items
- Content Parameters, Metadata or Linked Workflow Parameters - Content-level parameters and metadata
- OTP Tokens - One-time password tokens

### MIG-BPS-023: Data Sources for Migration
**Rule:** Different entities SHALL be retrieved from different sources:
- **OTP Tokens:** Retrieved from Redis
- **Document Activities:** Retrieved from versions custom content attached to every page or blogpost
- **Parameters, Metadata, Workflows, and Links:** Retrieved from Fireflow
  - This includes:
    - Content parameters
    - Content metadata
    - Workflow associations
    - Workflow links

### MIG-BPS-024: Data Transformations Required
**Rule:** Migration process SHALL require several data transformations:

**Fireflow Definitions → RoA Workflows:**
- Fireflow workflow definitions must be transformed to RoA workflow format
- Transformation logic needed to map Fireflow structure to RoA structure
- Must preserve all workflow configuration and logic

**Fireflow Resource Status → RoA Content State:**
- Fireflow resource status must be converted to RoA content state format
- State mappings and conversions required
- Must maintain state history and relationships

**Document Activity Entries Conversion:**
- Document activity entries from versions custom content must be converted to RoA Document Activity entries
- Format transformation required
- Must preserve activity history and metadata

**Content Parameters Consolidation:**
- Content workflow parameters and Page parameters are stored in different entities in Fireflow
- Both will be stored in the same table in RoA
- Consolidation and merging logic required
- Must ensure no data loss during consolidation

## SQL Table Provisioning Rules

### MIG-BPS-025: SQL Table Provisioning in CoF
**Rule:** CoF Application SHALL provision SQL tables:
- CoF application will create and manage all necessary SQL tables for the migration
- Tables will be provisioned using existing Forge SQL migration system
- All tables must be idempotent (use IF EXISTS/IF NOT EXISTS clauses)
- **MUST Reference:** `docs/database-schema.md` for complete schema definitions:
  - Table structures: Workflow, WorkflowLink, WorkflowLabel, WorkflowVersion, WorkflowParameter
  - Table structures: ContentState, ContentStateLabel, ContentApproval, ContentApprovalDecision
  - Table structures: ContentParameterAndMetadata, ContentParameterHistory, Messages, DocumentActivity, DocumentActivityUsers
  - Column types, constraints, primary keys, indexes
  - Foreign key relationships (only DocumentActivityUsers.activityId has explicit FK)
  - Logical relationships (all other relationships are logical, not enforced by FK constraints)

## Migration Monitoring Rules

### MIG-BPS-026: Migration Monitoring & Iteration
**Rule:** Migration SHALL support monitoring and iteration:
- Can monitor migration logs in real-time across all CoF customer installations
- Iterate on migration implementation based on real-world data and issues
- Retry and refine migrations until they are reliable and stable
- Validate migration success before RoA release

### MIG-BPS-027: Logging and Monitoring Setup
**Rule:** Logging and monitoring SHALL be configured:
- **Log Routing to Sumologic:**
  - Logs from CoF application must be routed to Sumologic
  - Logs from migration queue consumer must be routed to Sumologic
  - Centralized logging for migration visibility and debugging
- **Saved Searches:**
  - Create saved searches in Sumologic to monitor migration progress
  - Track migration success rates, failures, and retries
  - Monitor queue processing and webtrigger performance
- **Dashboards:**
  - Create dashboards in Sumologic to visualize migration metrics
  - Real-time monitoring of migration status across instances
  - Track batch migration progress and on-change migration activity
  - Monitor error rates and identify patterns

## Testing Rules

### MIG-BPS-028: Idempotency Testing
**Rule:** Idempotency SHALL be tested:
- Test that migrations are idempotent
- Test strategy for running migrations multiple times
- Verify no data duplication occurs on repeated execution
- Validation checks ensure migrations produce consistent results

## Strategy Coordination Rules

### MIG-BPS-029: Batch and On-Change Strategy Coordination
**Rule:** Both migration strategies SHALL work together:
- Batch migration establishes the baseline
- On-change migration captures ongoing modifications
- Both must be idempotent to allow safe retries
- Migration can run continuously during the CoF period

## Web Trigger Constraints (Inferred from Analysis)

### MIG-BPS-030: Static Webtrigger Constraints
**Rule:** Static Webtrigger batches SHALL respect:
- **Timeout:** 5 seconds (NOT 900s like Async Events)
- **Payload size:** ~1MB maximum
- **Rate limits:** Strict per tenant
- **Processing time:** Must complete within 5s
- **Batch validation:** Each batch must validate before sending:
  - `estimatedPayloadSize < 1MB`
  - `estimatedProcessingTime < 5s`
  - `batchSize <= maxBatchSize` where `maxBatchSize = min(chunkSize, floor(1MB / averageItemSize), itemsProcessableIn5s)`

**Note:** While the GitHub document doesn't explicitly state these constraints, they are critical Forge Web Trigger limits that must be respected.

## Versioning Constraints

### MIG-BPS-031: Minor Version Constraints
**Rule:** Since using minor version upgrades:
- Breaking changes are NOT allowed - all changes must be backward compatible
- API compatibility - all existing APIs and data structures must continue to work
- Gradual rollout - changes can be introduced incrementally across multiple minor versions

## Migration Phases

### MIG-BPS-032: Migration Phase Requirements
**Rule:** Migration SHALL follow these phases:

**Phase 1: Assessment and Planning**
- Assess current state
- Plan migration strategy

**Phase 2: Infrastructure Changes**
- Remove external dependencies
- Ensure all compute uses Forge runtime
- Ensure all storage uses Forge Storage/Forge SQL
- Provision SQL tables in CoF application
- Add migration triggers:
  - Hourly scheduled trigger for URL generation and registration
  - Static webtrigger (no data egress) for receiving migration data
  - Dynamic webtrigger (with data egress) for validation (CoF only)
- Implement URL persistence (Redis or user properties)
- Implement webhook endpoint for URL registration

**Phase 3: Code Refactoring**
- Refactor external API calls (must be backward compatible)
- Update analytics/logging to be customer-controllable
- Ensure data residency compliance
- All changes must maintain backward compatibility (minor version constraint)
- Implement migration strategies:
  - Batch migration for comprehensive data coverage
  - On-change migration for real-time synchronization

**Phase 4: Testing and Validation**
- Test in CoF environment
- Monitor migration logs across customer installations
- Iterate on migration implementation based on real-world data
- Retry and refine migrations until reliable
- Validate RoA compliance
- Test data compatibility
- Verify migration success before RoA release

**Phase 5: Deployment**
- Deploy RoA-compliant changes to CoF application (minor versions)
- Validate customer installations continue working
- Prepare RoA major version release
- Provide migration documentation for customers upgrading to RoA

**Phase 6: Parallel Support Period**
- Maintain both CoF and RoA applications simultaneously
- Support customers on both versions
- Coordinate bug fixes and updates for both versions
- Monitor customer upgrade patterns
- Plan deprecation timeline for CoF

## Risk Mitigation Rules

### MIG-BPS-033: Technical Risk Mitigation
**Rule:** Technical risks SHALL be mitigated:
- Maintaining two codebases/versions simultaneously
- Ensuring data compatibility between CoF and RoA
- Coordinating updates and bug fixes across both versions
- Risk of divergence between CoF and RoA implementations

### MIG-BPS-034: Business Risk Mitigation
**Rule:** Business risks SHALL be mitigated:
- Customer confusion during transition period
- Support burden of maintaining two versions
- Extended support period for CoF after RoA release
- Customer adoption rate of RoA version
- Risk of new customers installing CoF if not properly restricted
- Ensuring all new installations use RoA after release

## Data Residency Rules

### MIG-BPS-035: Data Residency Support
**Rule:** Application SHALL support data residency:
- App must support data residency that matches the host Atlassian app
- Data must remain in the same region as the Confluence instance

## Data Egress Control Rules

### MIG-BPS-036: Data Egress Control
**Rule:** Customers SHALL have full control over data egress:
- Analytics and logs must be configurable/blockable by customers
- No external API calls that bypass customer control

